  "prompt": "What is human right?",
  "response": "Human rights are fundamental rights and freedoms that belong to every person in the world from birth until death. They are based on the principles of dignity, equality, and respect, and cover various aspects of human existence, irrespective of nationality, ethnicity, or religion. These rights are often enshrined in international treaties, conventions, and national laws.\n\nKey principles include:\n\n1. **Universality**: Human rights apply to everyone equally, without discrimination.\n2. **Inalienability**: Human rights cannot be taken away, except in specific situations and according to due process.\n3. **Interdependence and indivisibility**: All rights, whether civil, political, economic, social, or cultural, are interconnected and equally important.\n\nSome examples of human rights are:\n\n- **Right to life, liberty, and security of person**.\n- **Freedom from torture and inhumane treatment**.\n- **Freedom of speech and expression**.\n- **Right to a fair trial**.\n- **Freedom of thought, conscience, and religion**.\n- **Right to work and receive educational opportunities**.\n- **Right to participate in government and public affairs**.\n\nGlobal organizations like the United Nations and various non-governmental organizations work to protect and promote human rights worldwide. The Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted by the United Nations General Assembly in 1948, is a foundational document that outlines the rights to which all humans are entitled.",
